					</div>
					<div class="col-xs-12 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
						<!-- End Wide Image -->
						<p>With lots of players doing things at the same time, often near to each other in-game, a server has to keep track of what happens and when ‚Äî to make sure everyone‚Äôs on the same page.</p>
						<p><strong>When the game state is calculated, the server transmits it to each connected player‚Äôs device</strong> ‚Äî after this, each player‚Äôs game world is refreshed.</p>
						<p>And this happens many times each second.</p>
						<!-- Tickrate -->
						<h2 class="mt-4" id="tickrate">Tickrate: the frequency of game state updates</h2>
						<p><strong>Tickrate is the number of times an updated game state is calculated and broadcast by a game server to players every second.</strong></p>
						<p>The higher the tickrate, the more precise a game simulation is.</p>
						<p>If a server sends 64 updates to players each second, it‚Äôs referred to as a ‚Äú64-tick‚Äù, or ‚Äú64 Hz‚Äù server (because Hertz, or Hz, is the unit of frequency).</p>
